         <abstract>
            <p>Let Ω(n) and ω(n) denote, respectively, the total number of prime factors and the number of distinct prime factors of the integer n. Euler proved that an odd perfect number N is of the form N = pem² where p ≡ e ≡ 1 (mod 4), p is prime, and p ∤ m. This implies that Ω(N) ≥ 2ω(N) – 1. We prove that Ω(N) ≥ (18ω(N) – 31)/7 and Ω(N) ≥ 2ω(N) + 51.</p>
         </abstract>
